Cardinality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 be sets.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 have the same 
\emph on
cardinality
\emph default
 when there exists a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon A\mapsto B$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|$
\end_inset

 the equivalence class of all sets with the same cardinality as 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and we simply call 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|$
\end_inset

 the cardinality of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the same cardinality as the empty set iff 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 itself is the empty set, written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|\coloneqq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the same cardinality as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3,\dots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We then write 
\begin_inset Formula $A\coloneqq n.$
\end_inset

 In this case we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
finite, 
\emph default
otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is of infinite cardinality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|A\right|\leq\left|B\right|
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
if there exists an injection from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|<\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|A\right|=\left|B\right|$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

